    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Girls, Gym and Health</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Wendy Shore letter on Aug 27 article on Chicago girls' public school deplores curriculum light on physical education</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In Chicago, Girls Get a Public School of Their Own'' (news article, Aug. 27):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In Chicago, Girls Get a Public School of Their Own'' (news article, Aug. 27):</p>
        <p>A disservice is being done to the girls in this school by a curriculum that is ''by necessity, somewhat light on physical education.'' You report (front page, Aug. 24) that the incidence of diabetes in the United States is rising sharply and is directly attributable to the increase in obesity, which results in increased high blood pressure, heart disease and circulatory problems. Establishing good exercise habits is a vital aspect of a good education.</p>
        <p>Inner-city girls have a hard problem finding safe places to be physically active and receive little cultural encouragement. To view physical education, which provides these things, as a frill is not only short-sighted; it is downright dangerous.</p>
        <p>WENDY SHORE  Orlando, Fla., Aug. 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
